&gt;
&gt;  The May variation is implied on pg13 in the example for &quot;mire&quot; (and
&gt;  elsewhere)

Yes, I remembered that one. It hardly seems like an alternate letter form to me.

&gt;  &gt;...and I don&#39;t see it in any of the QS fonts...
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;
&gt;  No font has ever been written to fully support QS. A few simulate a
&gt;  super tight kerning which is not remotely the same thing (obviously).
&gt;  Others include a few joined forms of vowel+Roe which has given rise to
&gt;  the erroneous notion that these are ligatures.

I realize that you&#39;re advocating a computational approach to Senior QS
(good luck!) that goes far beyond current fonts, but why do you say
that forms such as vowel+Roe are not ligatures?


&gt;  &gt;Regarding the alternate letter for They, the QM only says &quot;Letter No.8
&gt;  &gt;may connect on the writing-line by an allowable extension upward and
&gt;  &gt;forward...&quot; This is on page 13
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;
&gt;  Which of course implies They has a variation. Unless of course someone
&gt;  imagines this can be done by the rendering layer (fyi it absolutely
&gt;  can not)

My point here was simply that Read did not consider this variation to
be an alternate letter.


&gt;  &gt;True alternate letters are introduced on page 14
&gt;  &gt;under &quot;4 ALTERNATIVE LETTER-SYMBOLS&quot;.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;
&gt;  pg 14, incidentally, is in the Senior section of the manual. Read&#39;s
&gt;  items under that heading intentionally omits those letter forms which
&gt;  are obvious from examples elsewhere in the interest of clarity and
&gt;  brevity.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;I&#39;d be happier if we dropped May and They from this list.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;
&gt;  The variations for No and Utter are mentioned in the senior section of
&gt;  the QM. Junior has no more need for the alternative form of No or
&gt;  Utter than it needs the alternative May or They.

Yes, but it&#39;s easy enough to include these in a list of QS
letters--much easier than trying to enumerate letter connections. (See
my next post.)


&gt;  I regret to say, quite the reverse, that the list of alternate letters
&gt;  in proposal.txt is not exhaustive: on the bottom of pg 15 the word
&gt;  &quot;knife&quot; shows a variation for Fee, the example for Sea+Pea at the
&gt;  bottom of pg 13 has similar implications etc. (there are likewise
&gt;  ligatures few seem to notice like Sea+Utter)
&gt;  IMO either the list in proposal.txt should be entirely dropped or it
&gt;  should be entirely complete.
&gt;
&gt;  I know that the there is irresistible pressure for the Unicode
&gt;  proposal to be a snap shot of the first page of the QM. I recall
&gt;  reading a post wherein someone said they were &quot;allergic to extra
&gt;  Unicode points for senior&quot; which, as an argument, seems a tad weak to
&gt;  me. Personally I&#39;d like to see it done carefully and completely and in
&gt;  consultation with persons with a full understanding of QS even if this
&gt;  slows the process but I&#39;ve been avoiding the topic having notived that
&gt;  any proposal for completeness is futile.

I don&#39;t think it&#39;s futile at all--I just think you&#39;re the only one
who&#39;s going to do it. If you do, many of us will be quite interested
in what you produce.

Ted


